<div id="review_2871171993" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2871171993" />
    <a title="Lily Mordaunt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/98317965-lily-mordaunt"><img alt="Lily Mordaunt" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1640483227p2/98317965.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2871171993?book_show_action=true">Jul 18, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lily Mordaunt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lily Mordaunt" href="/user/show/98317965-lily-mordaunt">Lily Mordaunt</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2871171993" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4600017275758444563">I received the book for free after joining the author’s mailing list.<br/>I got the book nearly a year ago, and had plans to read it… Then school got in the way. Now, with summer here, I started it, found it enjoyable, but not necessarily compelling (Until the end).<br/>I loved the effortless inclusivity (the characters were a range of ethnicities and backgrounds and it didn’t feel forced), I also found the premise to be interesting and the author’s mythology to be original (The way she used established m</span>
  <span id="freeText4600017275758444563" style="display:none">I received the book for free after joining the author’s mailing list.<br />I got the book nearly a year ago, and had plans to read it… Then school got in the way. Now, with summer here, I started it, found it enjoyable, but not necessarily compelling (Until the end).<br />I loved the effortless inclusivity (the characters were a range of ethnicities and backgrounds and it didn’t feel forced), I also found the premise to be interesting and the author’s mythology to be original (The way she used established myths and made it into her own lore). And while I did enjoy the personalities of each of the main (and most of the supporting) characters, I particularly enjoyed Aranka, she felt real; a good balance between strong and vulnerable. It’s definitely understandable for characters to fall apart when their world has been turned upside down, it can get annoying to read. Especially if they don’t start working with their circumstances. However, with what she went through, I think Aranka’s reactions were all realistic/well thought out.<br />But as I said in the beginning, there was something about the story that just wasn’t compelling. That might have been me, and the blah State I was in when I started reading it, but it did take me a while to get through the beginning. I would read a chapter, and then put it down. And then yesterday, I started thinking about the story, wondering how things played out, picked it back up and flew through it (I was also really frustrated at the series I’m re-reading, so I was turning my mind to other options). It wasn’t necessarily unputdownable, but I am about to get the next book to see what happens.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4600017275758444563" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

